    Q :Suppose in a thread pool there are 10 threads
       Suppose one of fhe thread done its task so it again goes to theead pool ?
    Ans:Yes, that’s exactly how a thread pool works. Let me explain clearly in simple terms:

		A thread pool is a collection of pre-created threads that are reused to run tasks.

		Suppose your pool has 10 threads, and you submit multiple tasks to it.

		When a thread finishes a task, it does not die. Instead, it becomes idle and waits for the next task in the pool.

		The thread is reused for the next task that comes in, which saves the overhead of creating a new thread every time.

		So yes — once a thread completes its current task, it automatically goes back to the pool and waits for another 
		task. This is one of the main advantages of using a thread pool: efficient reuse of threads.

