Q9 : what is thread pool ? 
Ans - it is a group of all the available thread in our code/class/program.
      A thread pool is like a team of workers ready to do tasks. Instead of hiring a new worker 
	  for each job, you use the workers you already have in the pool. This makes getting work 
	  done faster and more efficient. 


Q18 : What is wait() ,notify() and notifyAll() method ? 
Ans  : wait() - wait() is a method of Object class when wait method is applied on the current thread then that 
       thread execution stops until  notify and notifyall methods are used by other thread.
	   (When a thread calls wait() on an object, it releases the lock on that object and pauses execution. 
	    It will remain paused until another thread calls notify() or notifyAll() on that same object.)
        
        here thread is calling the wait method not object is calling the wait method.        
		
		
       notify() - It is a method of Object class, is used to wake up one thread that is waiting(thread is waiting
	   not object is waiting) for an object.It will notify the next thread which is waiting. we have surity 
	   that which thread will be selected(because only one thread is waiting).
	   
       notifyAll() - notifyAll() method is used by thread to wake up all the waiting thread instead of a single 
	   thread. In notifyAll() we are not sure which thread will be selected because notification is send to all
       the threads which are waiting in waiting state so thread schedular decides which thread to go.	   
	   
	   Note - Synchronized keyword is must to use wait(),notify() and notifyAll().



Q19 : sleep() vs wait() ? 
Ans : 
Here is **sleep vs wait** in the **most simple way**:

---

## ✅ **sleep()**

* Comes from **Thread class**.
* **Does NOT release the lock**.
* Just pauses the current thread for some time.
* After time over → thread continues automatically.

**Think:**
👉 *“I’m taking a fixed-time nap. Don’t touch my lock.”*

---

## ✅ **wait()**

* Comes from **Object class**.
* Can be used **only inside synchronized block/method**.
* **Releases the lock**.
* Thread waits until **notify() / notifyAll()** wakes it up.

**Think:**
👉 *“I’m waiting for a signal. Meanwhile, you can use the lock.”*

---

## 🔥 **Super Simple Example**

### sleep():

```java
synchronized(obj) {
    Thread.sleep(2000); // Lock is NOT released
}
```

### wait():

```java
synchronized(obj) {
    obj.wait(); // Lock IS released
}
```

---

## 🎯 **Summary**

| Feature             | sleep() | wait()               |
| ------------------- | ------- | -------------------- |
| Class               | Thread  | Object               |
| Needs synchronized? | ❌ No    | ✅ Yes                |
| Releases lock?      | ❌ No    | ✅ Yes                |
| Wakes up by         | Time    | notify()/notifyAll() |

